rature -- tThe Book of Ben Sira and Deuteronomistic Heritage: A Critical Approach -- tThe Deuteronomic Legacy of 1 Maccabees -- tThe Deuteronomistic Ideology and Phraseology in the Book of Baruch -- tThe Use of Different Aspects of the Deuteronomistic Ideology in Apocryphal Psalms -- tJudith and Deuteronomistic Heritage -- tA Deuteronomic Heritage in Tobit? -- t5. Indices -- tIndex of Modern Authors -- tIndex of Passages0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe articles in this volume investigate changes in texts that became to be regarded as holy and unchangeable in Judaism and Christianity. The volume seeks to draw attention to the “empirical” evidence from Qumran, the Septuagint as well as from passages in the Hebrew Scriptures that have been shaped by the use of other texts. The contributions are divided into three main sections: The first section deals with methodological questions concerning textual changes. The second section consists of concrete examples from the Hebrew Bible, Qumran and Septuagint on how the texts were changed, corrected, edited and interpreted. The contributions of the third section will investigate the general influence and impact of Deuteronomistic ideology and phraseology on later texts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aDeuteronomistische Literatur. 4aHeilige Schrift. 4aParabiblische Literatur. 4aSchriftinterpretation. 4aZweiter Tempel. 7aRELIGION / Bible / Biography / General.2bisacsh  aDeuteronomistic Literature.  aParabiblical Literature.  aRewritten Scripture.  aScriptural Interpretation.  aSecond Temple Period.1 aAejmelaeus, Anneli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeentjes, Pancratius C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.